{{Galaxy cluster | name = Markarian's Chain | image = [[Image:MarkariansHunterWilson.jpg|300px]] | caption = Markarian's Chain in an amateur telescope | credit = | epoch = [[J2000]] | ra = {{RA|12|27}} | dec = {{DEC|+13|10}} | constellation = [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]] | member_no = 8 | brightest_member = | richness = | redshift = | distance = | temperature = | mass = | luminosity = | flux = | other_names = }} '''Markarian's Chain''' is a stretch of [[galaxies]] that forms part of the [[Virgo Cluster]]. When viewed from Earth, the galaxies lie along a smoothly curved line. [[Charles Messier]] first discovered two of the galaxies, [[Messier 84|M84]] and [[Messier 86|M86]], in 1781. The other galaxies seen in the chain were first mentioned in [[John Louis Emil Dreyer]]'s [[New General Catalogue]], published in 1888.<ref name=French2004>{{Cite journal |last=French |first=Sue |year=2004 |title=Deep-Sky Wonders: Markarian's Chain |journal=Sky & Telescope |volume=107 |issue=5 |pages=88–91}}</ref> It was ultimately named after the [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[astrophysicist]], [[Benjamin Markarian]], who discovered their common motion in the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal| bibcode=1961AJ.....66..555M| title=Physical chain of galaxies in the Virgo cluster and its dynamic instability| last=Markarian| first= B.E. | journal=Astronomical Journal| volume= 66| year= 1961| pages= 555–557}}</ref> Member galaxies include [[Messier 84|M84]] ([[NGC 4374]]), [[Messier 86|M86]] ([[NGC 4406]]), [[NGC 4477]], [[NGC 4473]], [[NGC 4461]], [[NGC 4458]], [[NGC 4438]] and [[NGC 4435]]. It is located at RA 12<sup>h</sup> 27<sup>m</sup> and Dec +13° 10′.
The bright members of the chain are visible through [[small telescope]]s. [[Large telescopes|Larger telescopes]] can be used to view the fainter galaxies.<ref name=French2004 />
At least seven galaxies in the chain appear to move coherently, although others appear to be superposed by chance.<ref>{{cite journal| bibcode=1983AN....304...69L| title=The Markarian chain of galaxies in the constellation Virgo| last=Litzroth| first= E.| journal=Astronomische Nachrichten| issn=0004-6337| volume= 304| issue= 2| year= 1983| pages= 69–72| doi=10.1002/asna.2113040204}}</ref> Six of the points on the chain can be marked by galaxies. The other two points are pairs of galaxies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meurers|first=J.|year=1977|title=Markarian's Chain of Galaxies in Virgo|url=|journal=Astronomische Nachrichten|volume=298|pages=103–106|doi=10.1002/asna.19772980206|bibcode = 1977AN....298..103M }}</ref>
