[[File:Mary Somerville On the Connexion of the Physical Sciences.jpg | thumb|right | ''On the Connexion of the Physical Sciences'', title page, 1834]]
'''''On the Connexion of the Physical Sciences''''' is one of the biggest selling science books in the 19th century.  It was written by [[Mary Somerville]] in 1834.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of ''On the Connexion of the Physical Sciences'' by Mrs. Sommerville|journal=The Quarterly Review|date=March 1834|pages=54–68|volume=51|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015074711394;view=1up;seq=64}}</ref>

The book went through many editions and was translated into several European languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/nature/v514/n7524/nature-2014-10-30.mp3|title=Nature Podcast|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref><ref name="Holmes2014">{{cite journal|last=Holmes|first=Richard|year=2014|title=In retrospect: On the Connexion of the Physical Sciences|journal=Nature|volume=514|issue=7523|pages=432–433|issn=0028-0836|doi=10.1038/514432a}}</ref><ref name="Secord2014">{{cite book|last=Secord|first=James|title=Visions of Science: Books and readers at the dawn of the Victorian age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gY0NAwAAQBAJ&pg=107|accessdate=5 November 2014|date=2014-03-18|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780191662751|pages=107–134}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=E. C.|author2=Eisberg, J|date=June 1985|title=Book Review: “The Queen of Nineteenth-Century Science”: Mary Somerville and the Cultivation of Science, 1815–1840|journal=Journal for the History of Astronomy|volume=16|issue=2|pages=144–146|doi=10.1177/002182868501600209|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1985JHA....16..144P|bibcode=1985JHA....16..144P}}</ref>  In a review of the book in March 1834, [[William Whewell]] coined the word "scientist".<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Scientist: The story of a word|url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/00033796200202722|journal = Annals of Science|date = 1962-06-01|issn = 0003-3790|pages = 65–85|volume = 18|issue = 2|doi = 10.1080/00033796200202722|first = Sydney |last =Ross }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = What is a scientific instrument, when did it become one, and why?|url = http://journals.cambridge.org/article_S0007087400044460|journal = The British Journal for the History of Science|date = 1990-03-01|issn = 1474-001X|pages = 86|volume = 23|issue = 01|doi = 10.1017/S0007087400044460|first = Deborah Jean|last = Warner}}</ref>

